// Help
"help.para.1" = "If you're wondering \"What's a Deutan?\" or something like that then let's try to demystify what's going on.

Any colour is a mix of three primary colours; blue, red and green. Colourblindness, or Colour Vision Deficiency (CVD), is the inability to correctly interpret one of those three colours.";

"help.para.1.a11y" = "If you're wondering \"What's a Deutan?\", or something like that, then let's try to demystify what's going on.

Any colour is a mix of three primary colours; blue, red, and green. Colourblindness, or Colour Vision Deficiency (CVD), is the inability to correctly interpret one of those three colours.";

"help.para.2" = "Somebody with normal colour vision is a **trichromat**, while a person with CVD is either an **anomalous trichromat** (they can see a certain amount of the colour they have a problem with), or a **dichromat** (they can't see it at all.)";

"help.para.2.a11y" = "Somebody with normal colour vision is a try chromat, while a person with CVD is either an anomalous try chromat (they can see a certain amount of the colour they have a problem with), or a die chromat (they can't see it at all.)";

"help.para.3" = "If a person with CVD has a problem seeing **blue**, they are a **Tritan**.

If a person with CVD has a problem seeing **red**, they are a **Protan**.

If a person with CVD has a problem seeing **green**, they are a **Deutan**.

If you want to be more precise you factor in if they have anomalous trichromacy or dichromacy.

A Tritan with anomalous trichromacy has **Tritanomaly**, and a Tritan with dichromacy has **Tritanopia**.

A Protan with anomalous trichromacy has **Protanomaly**, and a Protan with dichromacy has **Protanopia**.

A Deutan with anomalous trichromacy has **Deuteranomaly**, and a Deutan with dichromacy has **Deuteranopia**.";

"help.para.3.a11y" = "If a person with CVD has a problem seeing blue, they are a try-tan.
